I will provide a profile of the United States' educational system. The United States of America is a federal republic located in North America. It has approximately 328 million inhabitants and is known for its diverse culture and history. Although English is the official language, many other languages are also spoken throughout the country. The K-12 education system in the United States is primarily administered by state and local governments, with federal oversight and funding. The system consists of primary and secondary education, with primary education spanning kindergarten through fifth grade and secondary education spanning sixth through twelfth grade. Curriculum and standards vary by state and school district, but math, science, English, social studies, and foreign languages are generally emphasized. There are a variety of school types within the education system, including traditional public schools, charter schools, and private schools. Education Concern: The achievement gap, which refers to the persistent disparities in academic achievement and educational opportunities between different groups of students, particularly students from low-income families and students of color, is one of the major concerns in the United States. Principal Policies and Programs in Education: The No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) was enacted in 2001 as a federal law intended to improve academic achievement and hold schools accountable for student performance. The law has been criticized, however, for its emphasis on standardized testing and lack of resources for struggling schools. In 2015, the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) was passed to replace NCLB. It aims to provide states and districts with more options for improving schools and closing the achievement gap. Title I of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA) provides federal funding to schools with a significant proportion of low-income students. This funding is intended to assist in closing the achievement gap by providing resources and support to schools with the greatest need. Head Start provides low-income children and their families with comprehensive early childhood education, health, nutrition, and parent involvement services. The education system in the United States is diverse and complex, and there are ongoing efforts to improve student outcomes and reduce disparities. The achievement gap continues to be a significant concern that policymakers and educators continue to work to resolve. 